        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- AFFILIATE DISCLAIMER -->
    <AffiliateDisclaimer />

    <!-- INTRO SECTION -->
    <h2 id="why-kids-vitamins">What Children Actually Need From a Multivitamin</h2>

    <p>Children's nutritional requirements differ significantly from adults — both in the specific nutrients needed and the appropriate doses. Growing bones require adequate vitamin D and calcium. Developing brains depend on omega-3 DHA, iron, and B vitamins. Immune systems still building their defenses need vitamin C, zinc, and vitamin A. The challenge is that many children are picky eaters: studies show 25-35% of toddlers and preschoolers are classified as selective eaters, and even school-age children frequently consume inadequate amounts of the nutrients that matter most for development.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">70%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of US children have suboptimal vitamin D levels according to a 2024 CDC report. <strong>Iron deficiency remains the most common pediatric nutrient deficiency globally</strong>, affecting cognitive development, attention span, and academic performance. A well-formulated children's multivitamin addresses these critical gaps that diet alone frequently misses.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Gummy vitamins have transformed pediatric supplementation. Children who refuse chewable tablets or liquid vitamins will willingly — even eagerly — take a gummy vitamin. This compliance advantage is not trivial: the best supplement in the world provides zero benefit if a child refuses to take it. The trade-off is sugar content (2-4g per serving) and the inability to include certain nutrients in gummy form (iron and calcium are difficult to formulate in gummies). Understanding these trade-offs helps parents choose the right product for their child's specific needs.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sun" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Vitamin D3 — Bone Growth</strong>
        <p>Essential for calcium absorption, bone development, and immune function. 70% of US children have suboptimal levels. The AAP recommends 600 IU daily for children ages 1-18. Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is more effective than D2 (ergocalciferol).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Omega-3 DHA — Brain Development</strong>
        <p>DHA comprises 40% of the polyunsaturated fatty acids in the brain. It supports cognitive development, learning capacity, and attention span. Most children consume far below the 250mg DHA daily recommended by experts. Few kids' gummies include adequate DHA.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Zinc — Immune & Growth</strong>
        <p>Critical for immune cell development, wound healing, and linear growth. Zinc deficiency impairs taste perception — potentially worsening picky eating — creating a vicious cycle. Children ages 4-8 need 5mg daily; ages 9-13 need 8mg daily.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Iron — Cognitive Function</strong>
        <p>Iron deficiency is the most common pediatric nutrient deficiency worldwide. It impairs cognitive development, attention span, and academic performance. Most gummy vitamins do not contain iron (it is difficult to formulate in gummies and affects taste). Separate iron supplementation may be needed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <div class="warn-box-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={18} /></div>
      <p><strong>Always store gummy vitamins out of reach of children.</strong> Because they taste like candy, accidental overconsumption is a real risk. Iron-containing supplements pose the highest acute toxicity danger — iron overdose is a leading cause of poisoning deaths in children under 6. Use child-resistant containers and teach children that gummies are medicine, not candy. Contact Poison Control (1-800-222-1222) if overdose is suspected.</p>
