    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gummies for Kids</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do kids really need a multivitamin gummy?</summary>
      <p>Most children eating a balanced diet may not need one, but 25-35% of young children are picky eaters. Children with limited food variety, vegan/vegetarian diets, food allergies, or malabsorption conditions benefit most. A pediatrician can identify specific nutritional gaps.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What vitamins are most important for children?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin D (70% of kids have suboptimal levels), iron (most common pediatric deficiency), calcium (bone growth), vitamin A (vision and immunity), vitamin C (immune function), zinc (growth), B vitamins (brain development), and omega-3 DHA (cognitive development).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much sugar is in kids' gummy vitamins?</summary>
      <p>Most contain 2-4g per serving (about half to one teaspoon). The AHA recommends children consume fewer than 25g added sugar daily, so one gummy vitamin serving represents 8-16% of that limit. Sugar-free options exist but may have lower taste appeal.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>At what age can kids start taking gummy vitamins?</summary>
      <p>Most brands recommend ages 2 and older. Children under 2 should use liquid vitamin drops. For ages 2-3, supervise gummy consumption to prevent choking. Some products are formulated for ages 4+. Always check the specific product label and consult your pediatrician.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can kids overdose on gummy vitamins?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Iron-containing gummies pose the highest risk — iron overdose is a leading cause of poisoning deaths in children under 6. Fat-soluble vitamins A and D can accumulate to toxic levels. Store gummies in child-resistant containers out of reach. Contact Poison Control (1-800-222-1222) if overdose is suspected.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are organic kids' gummy vitamins worth the extra cost?</summary>
      <p>The vitamins themselves are equally effective. Organic certification means no synthetic pesticides, artificial colors, or GMOs — potentially important for developing children. The premium is 30-50% higher. If budget is tight, a USP Verified non-organic product provides equivalent nutrient quality.</p>
    </details>

